:formula_20
be the (scalar-valued) 2&quot;k&quot;-form on &quot;P&quot; given by
:formula_21
where &quot;v&quot;&quot;i&quot; are tangent vectors to &quot;P&quot;, formula_22 is the sign of the permutation formula_23 in the symmetric group on 2&quot;k&quot; numbers formula_24 (see Lie algebra-valued forms#Operations as well as Pfaffian).

If, moreover, &quot;f&quot; is invariant; i.e., formula_7, then one can show that formula_20 is a closed form, it descends to a unique form on &quot;M&quot; and that the de Rham cohomology class of the form is independent of formula_27. First, that formula_20 is a closed form follows from the next two lemmas:

:Lemma 1: The form formula_20 on &quot;P&quot; descends to a (unique) form formula_30 on &quot;M&quot;; i.e., there is a form on &quot;M&quot; that pulls-back to formula_20.
:Lemma 2: If a form of formula_32 on &quot;P&quot; descends to a form on &quot;M&quot;, then formula_33.

Indeed, Bianchi&#x27;s second identity says formula_34 and, since &quot;D&quot; is a graded derivation, formula_35 Finally, Lemma 1 says formula_20 satisfies the hypothesis of Lemma 2.

To see Lemma 2, let formula_37 be the projection and &quot;h&quot; be the projection of formula_38 onto the horizontal subspace. Then Lemma 2 is a consequence of the fact that formula_39 (the kernel of formula_40 is precisely the vertical subspace.) As for Lemma 1, first note
:formula_41
which is because formula_42 and &quot;f&quot; is invariant. Thus, one can define formula_30 by the formula:
